<DOC><DOCNO> AP880815-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-15-88 0747EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv23   08-15 0462</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv23,0480</SECOND><NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Aug. 23</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Tuesday, Aug. 23, the 236th day of 1988. There are 130days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   In the early morning hours of Aug. 23, 1927, Italian-bornanarchists Nicola Sacco and Bartolomeo Vanzetti were executed inBoston for the murders of two men during a 1920 payroll robbery.The case had drawn widespread controversy, with many convinced thatSacco and Vanzetti had been convicted for their political beliefs.   On this date:   In 1754, France's King Louis XVI was born at Versailles.   In 1785, U.S. naval hero Oliver Hazard Perry was born in SouthKingstown, R.I.   In 1838, one of the first colleges for women, Mount HolyokeFemale Seminary in South Hadley, Mass., graduated its firststudents.   In 1914, Japan declared war on Germany in World War I.   In 1926, silent film star Rudolph Valentino died in New York atage 31.   In 1944, Romanian prime minister Ion Antonescu was overthrown,paving the way for his country to abandon the Axis in favor of theAllies.   In 1947, an audience at the Hollywood Bowl heard President HarryS. Truman's daughter, Margaret, give her first public concert as asinger.   In 1960, Broadway librettist Oscar Hammerstein II died inDoylestown, Pa.   In 1972, the Republican national convention, meeting in MiamiBeach, Fla., nominated Vice President Spiro T. Agnew for a secondterm. (The vote was overwhelming, but not unanimous _ one vote wentto NBC newsman David Brinkley.)   In 1979, Soviet dancer Alexander Godunov defected while theBolshoi Ballet was on tour in New York.   Ten years ago: Leftist guerrillas who had seized the NationalPalace in Managua, Nicaragua, the day before threatened to executetheir hostages unless their demands, which included the release ofpolitical prisoners, were met.   Five years ago: In an address to the American Legion in Seattle,President Reagan charged that the anti-nuclear movement ``wouldwage peace by weakening the free. That just doesn't make sense.''   One year ago: Seven Democratic presidential hopefuls tradedgentle barbs at a debate in Des Moines, Iowa, with MassachusettsGov. Michael Dukakis repeatedly called upon to defend his claims ofeconomic revival in his home state.   Today's birthdays: Actor-dancer Gene Kelly is 76. Orchestraleader Bob Crosby is 75. Actress Vera Miles is 58. Politicalsatirist Mark Russell is 56. Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., is 55.Actress Barbara Eden is 54. Ballet dancer Patricia McBride is 46.Actress Shelley Long is 39. Actor-singer Rick Springfield is 39.Queen Noor of Jordan is 37.   Thought for today: ``If you board the wrong train, it is no userunning along the corridor in the other direction.'' _ DietrichBonhoeffer, German theologian (1906-1945).</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv</NOTE></DOC>